segments.text: Have you always been interested in war gaming and fantasy gaming?
How did you start getting interested in this?
No, I haven't always been interested in it.
I didn't know anything about war gaming until Dungeons & Dragons came out.
Dungeons & Dragons arrived commercially in California in 1974.
And my children, I have two grown sons now,
had heard about it from some friends at school and told me about it
because they were sure I would be interested, and I was.
We went out and bought a copy of the game and tried to learn to play it.
And I actually learned about the other kinds of war gaming with miniature soldiers
and things like that from playing Dungeons & Dragons.
And reading about that and going to the stores where they sell it.
That was about the time that I wrote to Gary Gygax, who's the inventor of Dungeons & Dragons,
or the co-inventor of Dungeons & Dragons,
and told him that the original set of instruction booklets that they had put out
was impossible really to understand if you hadn't seen a game played.
If you had seen somebody play a game, you could then go back to the rule books
and pick out the information that you needed.
And that what they needed was an introductory book for people who had never seen a game.
And he wrote me back a nice letter and said,
And would you be willing to try writing such a book?
I wrote what is usually called the basic set rule books about 70-odd pages long
on how to learn to play Dungeons & Dragons.
It's in the second edition now, and the second edition has been edited by somebody else.
And I'm listed as the editor and not the writer,
because Gygax and Aronson really wrote the game,
and all I did was edit it.
So I think it was a lot easier for a beginner to understand.
Which one of the sets of rules that you edited?
Well, as I say, it's called basic set Dungeons & Dragons.
And it sells in a box with usually a module game and some odds and ends.
And the new edition has a different picture on the box
and has been edited by somebody else who is credited with editing it.
If you've ever seen it, it's a blue pamphlet with a big dragon on the cover.
Yeah, that's the one that I had.
Now, what I was getting after was, which of the books did you take?
Which of the original books did you take and then compile or edit down into?
Well, that's one of the problems with the original set of little booklets.
Gygax and Aronson were playing the game,
and there was a demand from people who had heard about it for a rule set.
And they sat down and wrote up the thing.
They'd published some rules, or Gygax had published some rules for other games before.
And they made up three little booklets.
And the rules for how to play the game were just scattered through the three books kind of at random.
And there's very little in the way of table of contents and no index.
So that it's impossible to find something except by flipping through the pages of all three of the books.
And then they put out a series of supplements.
And new rules were included in those kind of at random as well.
So what I did was go through all that stuff and try and make a coherent little booklet out of it
so that a beginner could start out and devise characters and plan a scenario and play through a game without being totally lost.
Can you give us a little bit of background about how Vengeance and Dragons got started?
I can tell you my understanding of it from having talked to Gary Gygax.
Gary had been playing war games with miniature figures for years.
And he and some friends had devised a series of rules for medieval warfare, armored knights and horseback and things like that.
And they had included, since everybody had read Tolkien's Lord of the Rings,
they had included in those rules, rules for how to fight trolls and goblins and dragons and other kinds of creatures out of the books.
So they had a, it was called chain mail.
It was a little set of rules which was predominantly how to fight toy soldier battles.
The people who do war gaming don't like to have them called toy soldiers.
They like to have them called miniature figures.
But somebody coming into the field from outside would think of them as toy soldiers.
How to fight the battles using the fantasy elements.
And then Aronson had designed the first dungeon.
And run some games in which people had to do a quest inside a dungeon and find a treasure and read maps and hunt their way through and kill the monsters who were in there.
And that's essentially what the game is.
They just combine those two elements together.
And more people heard about it.
And the game spread by word of mouth.
And they published this little set of rule books.
And again, the publicity, as far as I know, was entirely by word of mouth from like science fiction conventions or game conventions.
More and more people heard about it.
More and more people bought the rule books.
And the thing was with gradually booming.
It took Gygax a year or so to sell his first set of rule books.
And, of course, now he runs a million-dollar industry with 30 or 40 employees making up not only Dungeons & Dragons with other kinds of games.
But really, it's a company that Dungeons & Dragons created.
Now, fixing to ask you a really broad question here that you have answered in your book.
But what do you suppose is behind the popularity of the Dungeons & Dragons game?
Well, I think that, to begin with, there isn't any one answer to that.
The answer that Gygax gives is to say, well, in modern life, people don't get to have interesting adventures.
And so there's a real need in everybody's heart to be an adventurer.
And here's a chance to do that in the course of a game without actually getting hurt doing it.
And I think that that is part of it.
I'm sure that the popularity of Tolkien's Lord of the Rings was part of it.
Of course, you can then ask me why was Tolkien's Lord of the Rings so popular,
and I'm not sure that I know the entire answer to that either.
But playing the game is different from reading a story.
If you read a story, you can kind of imagine yourself being the hero.
And if the story's well written, you can really get into the hero's problems,
and you can see the wonders that he sees and the excitement that he experiences.
And with a good author, you can really enjoy that.
But you have to do what the author says the hero does, if you're imagining being that hero.
So you can close the book and imagine how you might have handled things
or what might happen if you had lived in those times.
And there were a lot of people in the country at the time that Dungeons & Dragons were created
who kind of had daydreams about what they would do if they were hobbits
or if they were dwarves or if they were elves or heroes.
And in the game, you come a lot closer to being a hobbit or a dwarf or an elf or a hero or a wizard
than you do in just reading about it or that you do in just imagining it all by yourself
because you have several other people playing with you.
And let's say you decide that you want to be a wizard,
and all your friends agree that you are a wizard or that your character in the game,
but you start talking about that person as if it were yourself, is a wizard.
And for, you know, four to six hours once a week in the evening,
you feel like you really are that person.
And that's a lot more exciting than just reading about such a person.
That your alternate reality persona becomes a very real thing.
And when a person like that gets killed in the course of the game,
as happens extremely frequently, people get very upset
because it's a real part of themselves that gets destroyed.
I think it's a marvelous invention.
It's a combination of play acting and creative storytelling and regular game mechanics.
The regular game mechanics are involved in rolling dice to decide who wins a battle
or whether a spell goes off and things like that or whether the trap door jam's shut.
The game mechanics are quite complicated,
but they're just a way of putting a chance factor into things.
And I don't think, really, that there'd been anything before that was quite comparable to it.
And I suspect that it would have caught on at any particular period in history.
I think it just happened to be invented in the 1970s.
But it happened to be invented and happened to be invented about a fantasy world.
You know, there are role-playing games about almost anything else you can imagine.
There's a role-playing game in which you pretend to be a gunslinger in the Wild West.
As a matter of fact, there are several.
There are role-playing games in which you pretend to be a comic book superhero.
For people who have read Watership Down,
there are role-playing games in which you pretend to be a talking rabbit.
So that you can, once you've mastered the basic principles of role-playing games,
you can take on any kind of alternate reality that you want
and pretend to be just about anything as long as you can get some friends to play with you and to agree.
They have to agree, of course, to allow you to do that.
Does that answer the question, or did I just wander beside it there for a while?
No, that answered the question very well.
I'm going to be at a loss to figure out exactly what to cut out in order to make that fit into a show.
You've got a university professor on the phone who's accustomed to giving 50-minute lectures,
and I rarely answer a question in short order.
The factors that led to the wide acceptance of the game, I think,
have to do with the fact that the game is a unique experience.
It's really different than playing most games,
and it's different than reading an imaginative story.
It's a little more active and a little more exciting.
And so it has appealed to a large number of people,
but quite a few women as well.
And, you know, I think it just turned out,
Gygax was lucky, it turned out that there was a big audience waiting for something like that.
Yeah, in my research, such as it is,
I've come to that self-same conclusion that
Dungeons and Dragons was something whose time had come,
and Gygax just happened to be the person who came up with it.
Yeah, isn't that so often true of any invention or fad, right,
that catches on is that there's an audience ready for something like this,
and then somebody is lucky enough to come up with something that catches their imagination.
And then it spreads very rapidly.
One of the things that impresses me about Dungeons and Dragons
was how rapidly it spread with, as far as I know,
in the beginning, no advertising at all.
Now, of course, there's a big advertising campaign.
To continue to increase the audience.
What is your involvement with TSR right now?
Well, I have no official relationship to TSR,
except that, you know, I have some friends there,
and I would count Gygax as a personal friend.
And he made an arrangement with me when I edited the beginner's book
that they would supply me with games and magazines for free for the rest of my life.
So I get a copy of everything that the company produces.
And I attend the conventions, and usually when I do that, I do some beginner's games,
because I figure that the thing that I'm most expert at is how to learn to play.
But I don't have any official position with the company or really any contract or anything else with them.
The book, Fantasy Role-Playing Games, was written for another company entirely.
And as an attempt to cover the entire field, not just the Dungeons & Dragons part itself,
although Dungeons & Dragons is the most important part of the role-playing game field.
Yes, I did get your book from, let's see, Hippocrine.
Hippocrine Press in New York, not one of your better-known publishing companies.
They do, however, publish a number of books in wargaming,
and that's how I came in contact with them.
They published a book on board wargames, which I thought was very good,
and had a lot of nice photographs in it,
and I wrote to them and suggested that I write a book about this kind of games,
and they were glad to do that.
Yeah, I read your article in Locus Magazine a couple of issues back,
and that's what got me trying to track you down.
Well, I'm glad to know that somebody had read the review in Locus.
I prepared a second review to cover other kinds of science fiction games,
but they decided that that was enough.
After they published that first one.
I also wrote an article in Psychology Today called Confessions of a Dungeon Master,
and a little bit about the psychology of people playing a role-playing game.
And I frequently get telephone interviews on the basis of that.
That actually has had wider circulation than the Locus article or the book.
was when that article in Psychology Today came out.
And it has a tremendous illustration that one of the artists for the magazine did.
I tell a story about, I'm a professor at the USC Medical School,
and I tell a story about the fact that I have a game of Dungeons & Dragons,
I did at that time, I don't know, that I dungeon mastered every month,
that the game players were mostly doctors and medical students and nurses and scientists from the medical school.
And the artists do an illustration showing a series of monsters sitting around the gaming table,
moving little figures which represent doctors and nurses and scientists on a huge board.
There must have been playing a game that I came up with called Doctors and Ditch Diggers.
You see, you can make up a role-playing game to fit any particular role that you're interested in playing.
There's a cartoon that TSR published, too,
in which the wizard and the dwarf and the elf are sitting around the table,
and they say it's a game called Papers and Paychecks,
in which we pretend to be students and workers in an industrial society.
Yeah, that's in the DM's Guide.
Let's explode a few myths here, or misconceptions, as they were.
Tell us about the story of the kid from Minnesota and what really happened.
Wasn't there a college student from Michigan who got killed playing live Dungeons and Dragons
in the steam tunnels under Michigan State University?
There was a college student at University of Michigan, or Michigan State, I've forgotten which it was,
who disappeared and his family couldn't find him.
He was a Dungeons and Dragons player.
And one of the things that the investigators, and they hired a private detective, family hired a private detective to try and locate him.
One of the things that he found was a series of maps, which were probably Dungeons and Dragons maps, a lot of mysterious maps.
And somebody suggested that they were maps of the steam tunnels underneath the university and that people had been playing Dungeons and Dragons in the steam tunnels.
As far as I know, that's never really been proven to be the case, that anybody was actually playing in the steam tunnels.
He showed up, and I think he had gone to visit some member of his family some distance away.
And when there was enough publicity, there was a lot of publicity about this.
A lot of television and radio news coverage of it when it occurred.
Partly, I think, because the news media people sensed that this was a weird cult, like the Jonestown massacre thing, which had occurred a year or so before.
And they thought they were on to something really bizarre.
But he turned up alive, and his disappearance had to do with his own personal life and his own personal problems, I guess.
And it had nothing to do with his playing Dungeons and Dragons.
But as far as I know, that's where the story ends.
You know, there are rumors about what's happened to him since, but I don't know of any secure information.
There's been one novel based on that incident.
It's called Mazes and Monsters, and it's by Rona Jaffe.
And it's about college students who are playing a game called, not Dungeons and Dragons, but Mazes and Monsters.
And the students get very involved in the game, and they all have deep psychological problems.
And one of them flips out and thinks that he's really the character that he plays in the game.
The psychology of it is, I think, rather badly flawed.
But I say that as a professional person who deals with abnormal psychology.
As a psychological thriller of a novel, I think it's really very good.
I plan to read it before I put together this program.
You know, it's well written, and I really got worried about those college students.
You know from page one that one of them is going to lose his or her mind,
and you really worry about who it's going to be and what's going to happen to him.
So I won't spoil it for you by telling you what happens.
It has a surprise ending, I'll tell you that.
And there's supposed to be another novel and maybe a movie based on the disappearance thing in the works.
The people at PSR Hobbies, as far as I know, were really very unhappy about the whole business,
particularly about the weird cult publicity that they got.
Although apparently they got so much publicity that they ended up selling a lot more games in the long run
and not doing them any harm.
But they weren't particularly overjoyed about it, I know,
any more than they are about the publicity they get.
Every once in a while, somebody suggests that the game should not be played in public schools
or, you know, should not be taught after school or something like that
because it is an initiation into the occult and into demonology.
Why don't you elaborate on that a little bit and see if you can,
no, not see if you can, you already have in your book,
give the same reasons how come this isn't the case.
Well, the accusation usually is that the game is dangerous
of course the people who are playing the game are frequently adults and not children,
but, you know, it depends on what age you consider to be a child,
and there certainly are plenty of people 12 years old playing the game,
teaching them, you know, evil occult and demonological ritual.
And the people who make these accusations, as it turns out,
are extremely religious people, fundamentalist religious people,
who really believe in the existence of the devil and his demons.
And demons are in the game.
There are rules for playing demons.
I rarely use them in my own game because I prefer to use monsters out of other sources,
literature, or dinosaurs or something like that,
just because they're more fun for me.
But there certainly are rules for using demons.
And if you really believed in the existence of demons,

But the reason that there are demons in the game

I haven't heard anybody in any way being worried about that.
I haven't heard about, you know,
Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Dragons or something
But the flap over the use of the game,

usually ends up to be involved with this controversy

then you don't want to have it as a game

I've read some of the religious tracks that have been published about,

There is a lot of violence in the game.
